# 6 Carat Round Diamond Price: The Six-Figure Threshold

![6 carat round diamond face-up showing 11.7mm diameter compared to 1ct, 3ct, and 5ct round diamonds on white editorial background](/images/6-carat-round-diamond-price-1.avif)

## TL;DR: 6 Carat Round Diamond Price — Key Facts

- **Entry price** for a GIA Excellent 6ct round diamond (G-VS2) is **$187,650** on Blue Nile — that's $31,100 per carat
- The per-carat cost at 6ct is **9.6× higher** than a 1ct G-VS2 at $3,230 per carat — rarity pricing, not markup
- A 6ct round measures approximately **11.7mm** in face-up diameter — 83% wider than a 1ct stone
- VS2 clarity stays eye-clean in round brilliants even at 6ct; VS1 adds certainty without the VVS premium
- **Lab-grown 6ct IGI D-VVS1 Excellent costs $18,410** — 90% less than the natural entry with identical face-up optics
- Upgrading to D-FL over G-VS2 adds **$246,250** for a color difference invisible to the naked eye in a mounted ring

---

Six carats is where the diamond market changes its rules. Below this threshold, round diamonds appear in engagement ring searches, high-street jewelry stores, and mainstream auction results. At 6ct, you are in a different category: Blue Nile typically carries only 12–16 natural GIA Excellent 6ct round diamonds at any given time, compared to 400–600 at the 1ct level.

This guide gives you the real numbers from Blue Nile's current inventory — 18 stones across natural and lab-grown — along with the per-carat math, the six specification points that matter most at this size, and a straight answer on whether the lab-grown 6ct changes the calculation entirely.

---

## What a 6 Carat Round Diamond Actually Looks Like

A 6ct round brilliant measures approximately 11.7mm in face-up diameter. To put that in context:

| Carat Weight | Diameter | Face-Up Area |
|---|---|---|
| 1ct | 6.4mm | 32 mm² |
| 2ct | 8.1mm | 52 mm² |
| 3ct | 9.4mm | 69 mm² |
| 4ct | 10.2mm | 82 mm² |
| 5ct | 11.0mm | 95 mm² |
| **6ct** | **11.7mm** | **107 mm²** |

That 11.7mm face-up area is 3.3× the surface area of a 1ct round. On a standard size-6 finger (16.5mm visible width), a 6ct stone covers 71% of the finger. It does not require good lighting or close proximity to be noticed — it announces itself.

The face-up diameter also means the stone extends beyond most standard ring shanks on both sides, which affects setting choice significantly. At 11.7mm, a thin prong solitaire looks architecturally top-heavy; wider band profiles and more substantial prong designs balance the stone correctly.

