The two G-VS2 stones at $187,650 and $206,360 are priced differently because of proportions. Both carry the same GIA Excellent grade, but the one at $206,360 likely has tighter crown/pavilion angle alignment within the Excellent specification. Always verify table percentage, crown angle, and pavilion angle on the GIA report — not just the cut grade.

The G-VS1 jump from $187,650 to $198,400 adds $10,750 for a clarity grade that requires 10× magnification to detect. In a round brilliant with 57 facets scattering light across the stone, VS2 inclusions at 6ct remain eye-clean. That $10,750 clarity premium is certificate premium, not visual premium.

